Doc,<br><br>
I don't think your way of thinking is an oversimplification at all. I will go one step further and say that the Vietnamese peasant was not overly concerned with material things. He existed in a culture and civilization that was thousands of years older than ours, yet for some reason he was considered &quot;backward&quot;.<br><br>
There was not a &quot;good choice&quot; between communism or the corruption in the south. However, given the choice between war or no war, I believe that the &quot;average peasant&quot; would have chosen &quot;no war&quot; in order for him to continue existing as he existed for thousands of years. I base this opinion on the devastation and misery that I personally witnessed. <br><br>
As for our Civil War, it is very well known that had the British entered the war on the side of the south, many southerners would have considered this an &quot;invasion&quot;. Your correlation between our civil war and the Vietnamese civil war is correct, in my opinion.<br>

